/* --- ACTIVE PROJECT LOAD --- 
Calculates the mean number of employees assigned per project. Used to monitor resource allocation density.
*/

Average Project Load = 
 VAR totalProjects = DISTINCTCOUNT(BridgeEmployeeProject[Project ID])
 VAR totalActiveEmployees = DISTINCTCOUNT(BridgeEmployeeProject[Employee ID])
 RETURN
    DIVIDE(totalActiveEmployees, totalProjects, 0)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/* --- AVERAGE PROJECT DURATION (DAY) ---
Calculates the mean lifecycle of projects in days by iterating through the Projects table and computing the variance between Start and End dates. This operational metric helps identify trends in project complexity and supports more accurate resource forecasting and timeline estimation.
*/

Average Project Duration (Day) = AVERAGEX(Projects, DATEDIFF(Projects[Start Date], Projects[End Date], DAY)) 

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/* --- REPEAT CUSTOMER RATE ---
Calculates the percentage of the customer base that has engaged in more than one project. Logic: Creates a virtual table to count unique projects per Customer ID, filters for counts > 1, and divides by the total unique customer count. This retention metric is a key indicator of customer satisfaction and brand loyalty.
*/

Repeat Customer Rate = 
VAR customerProjectTable = ADDCOLUMNS(VALUES(ProjectSales[Customer ID]), "Project Count", DISTINCTCOUNT(ProjectSales[Project ID]))
VAR customersMoreThanTwoProjectsCnt = COUNTROWS(FILTER(customerProjectTable, [Project Count] > 1))
RETURN
    DIVIDE(customersMoreThanTwoProjectsCnt, DISTINCTCOUNT(ProjectSales[Customer ID]))

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/* --- DAILY BURN RATE ---
Calculates the average daily expenditure by dividing the total cost by the number of elapsed days within the current date context. Logic: Determines the temporal span (start to end) and adds a +1 day buffer to ensure the divisor is inclusive. This operational efficiency metric is critical for monitoring liquidity and forecasting the exhaustion of project budgets.
*/

Daily Burn Rate = 
    VAR startDate = MIN(ProjectSales[Date])
    VAR latestDate = MAX(ProjectSales[Date])
RETURN
    DIVIDE(SUM(ProjectSales[Cost]), DATEDIFF(startDate, latestDate, DAY) + 1, 0)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/* --- CROSS-FUNCTIONAL PROJECT RATIO ---
Calculates the proportion of projects requiring collaboration across multiple departments. Logic: Generates a virtual table to count unique departments per project ID using a bi-directional CROSSFILTER, filters for counts > 1, and divides by the total project count. This metric highlights organizational silo-breaking and the complexity of inter-departmental resource integration.
*/

Cross-Functional Project Ratio = 
// 1. We find how many departments are involved in each project
VAR ProjectDepartmentCountTable = ADDCOLUMNS(VALUES(BridgeEmployeeProject[Project ID]), "DeptCount", CALCULATE(DISTINCTCOUNT(Employee[Department]), CROSSFILTER(BridgeEmployeeProject[Employee ID], Employee[Employee ID], Both)))

// 2. Finding the number of projects in which employees from more than one department are involved--cross-functional projects
VAR crossDepartmentalProjectsCount = COUNTROWS(FILTER(ProjectDepartmentCountTable, [DeptCount] > 1))

// 3. Finding the total number of projects 
VAR totalProjects = DISTINCTCOUNT(Projects[Project ID])
RETURN
    DIVIDE(crossDepartmentalProjectsCount, totalProjects, 0)

